##Could the Olympics become the Winter Olympics? Japan Olympics minister: Tokyo Olympics may be postponed to the end of

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

Japan's Olympic minister, Seiko Hashimoto, said Wednesday on whether the outbreak of pneumonia could lead to the cancellation of this summer's games in Tokyo, "The agreement calls for the Games to be held by 2020, which could be interpreted as allowing them to be postponed until the end of the year. "

Under the agreement, the right to postpone or cancel the Games belongs to the International Olympic Committee, and the Japanese government and Tokyo are making every effort to keep the Games on schedule, which starts on July 24, Seiko Hashimoto said.

Photograph: CCTV News

A total of 976 cases of new pneumonia were confirmed in Hokkaido, Kanagawa Prefecture and Ehime Prefecture as of 20 pm local time Tuesday, the NHK reported. The confirmed cases included 257 infected people in Japan and Chinese tourists, 705 passengers and crew members of the Diamond Princess cruise ship and 14 people who were flown home by chartered planes. In addition, there were 12 cumulative deaths.

Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe said on Feb. 26 that he would "spare no effort to ensure the holding of the Tokyo Olympics, " according to overseas reports.

"The end of May may become the deadline for a final decision. "

According to Reference News, Hashimoto said the two sides only limited the contract to 2020 to hold the Olympic Games, there is no specific date. Under the contract, Tokyo could postpone the Games until the end of the year at the latest.

But she stressed that the Japanese government and Tokyo were still pushing for the opening scheduled for July 24.

She said there was no official decision on when to judge whether the Tokyo Olympics would be held on time. But in her judgment, the end of May could become the deadline for a final decision.

The latest estimates put Japan's budget for the Games at 1.35 trillion yen, she said in a statement.

According to the Olympic host agreement, the right to cancel the games belongs to the International Olympic Committee. Bach, the president of the International Olympic Committee, said last week that despite the spread of the coronavirus, the International Olympic Committee would "spare no effort" to ensure the Tokyo Olympics were held as scheduled.

There was talk of a ban on spectators

On March 3, the Daily Mail reported that there had been discussions among the International Olympic Committee, the WHO and the sport's governing bodies, according to Stephen Parker, president of the British Cycling Association, a plan to host the Tokyo Olympics without spectators.

With the global epidemic not being effectively contained in the run-up to the Games, holding the games behind closed doors may be a viable alternative to cancelling events or switching to other venues. And of all the contingency plans, open play is a relatively inexpensive option.

If the Games are held in an empty venue, the camera crew can be allowed to enter for television coverage to meet the high value of the contract already signed. Aside from the loss in ticket sales, the Japanese authorities and the International Olympic Committee have been able to minimise their losses on all fronts.

Although the empty field competition can reduce the loss, but its disadvantage lies in, the athlete participates in itself is also a kind of gathering behavior, can not avoid the infection risk completely. Especially for international events with a more complex source of players, this form is still risky.

For the first time since 1945, Japan's domestic j league has been postponed, while sumo wrestling is held in an empty field.

A spokesman for the International Olympic Committee said: "Olympic organisers are working with the WHO and Japan to monitor the situation before any definitive decision is made. "

Anbe responded: We will do everything we can to ensure that the Tokyo Olympics are held

On Feb. 26, Anbe attended a focus session of the Budget Committee of Japan's Lower House of parliament, foreign media reported. In response to a question from NDP representative Yukio Ichiro, Anbe said that "as a government, we want to do our best to hold [ the event ] in a secure and safe environment" .

"As the government, we will continue to work closely with the IOC, the International Olympic Committee, and the Tokyo metropolitan government to ensure that the Games are safe and secure for both athletes and spectators, " Anbe added.

It is understood that recently, International Olympic Committee Commissioner Duecker Pound had pointed out that "if the threat of a new pneumonia epidemic can not be eliminated after three months, the 2020 Tokyo Olympic Games may be cancelled" , this statement also immediately triggered international public opinion, to be the center of attention. The International Olympic Committee later responded by saying that the International Olympic Committee was working hard to make the Tokyo Olympics a success, but otherwise it was all speculation.

In response to Pound's remarks, Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga said on the 26th that Pound's views are his own and not those of the International Olympic Committee. The Tokyo Olympics will go ahead as planned.

The Tokyo Games are scheduled to be held from July 24 to August 9. The Olympic torch relay will officially begin on March 26 at J-village, the transit site for the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear power plant, during a 121-day tour of Japan's 47 prefecture of Japan cities, and Lit the cauldron at the opening ceremony of Tokyo's new national arena on July 24.

Source: Daily Economic News Integrated CCTV news, Reference News, overseas web, interface news
